to make a "virtual" sequence object with the desired interpretation.

`pipeline` is already working. So if `set_process_func` is in this PR, I bet that within a few months it will be torn out. But my comment is more of an advisory than a requirement for this PR; someone else can make that change as we update all the other reader classes.

for reference, here's a similar test from the brave java project

```java
  // This prevents the server timestamp from overwriting the client one
  @Test public void doesntReportServerTimestampOnSharedSpans() {
    MutableSpan span = new MutableSpan(context.toBuilder().shared(true).build(), localEndpoint);

    span.start(1L);
    span.kind(SERVER);
    span.finish(2L);

    assertThat(span.toSpan()).extracting(s -> s.timestamp, s -> s.duration)
        .allSatisfy(u -> assertThat(u).isNull());
  }
```

Could you shorten this, by using UnIndex' _get_object_datum method? For example:
```
if component.meta_type == 'FieldIndex':
    attr = component.attributes[-1]
    datum = self._get_object_datum(obj, attr)
    if isinstance(datum, list):
        datum = tuple(datum
    return (datum,)
```

This isn't what we want here.  The only use of these two functions is to be able to serialize the SBInterpolatedKImage more efficiently than the version we get by using `repr`.  Calling `fillKValue` is not very efficient.  

For SBInterpolatedImage, it was fine to take the view of the XTable, since that has the right shape and it doesn't actually require copying any values to make the ImageView, so it is efficient to pass that back and reasonably efficient to remake the SBInterpolatedImage from that.

Here, KTable stores things in a different order than the input images, so getting a view of the real and imag parts wouldn't be the right thing to input back as a the real and imag images in the constructor. Which is why you implemented these functions this way.  But if we're going to do all this, it's probably better to just keep the originals around and use them again.

However, I think a better option would be to make an alternate version of the constructor that would accept the raw KValue data as input and efficiently recreate the KTable.  I'd suggest adding the centroid values to the arg list so if they have been calculated, then it would avoid recalculating those as well.  (You'd also need the bool flag of whether they are calculated or not yet.)

Then instead of these two functions, we would have one function that returns the KValue data packaged up as an Image, but not really being any kind of useful image.

```
template <typename T>
    SBInterpolatedKImage::SBInterpolatedKImageImpl::SBInterpolatedKImageImpl(
        const BaseImage<double>& data,
        double dk, double stepk, boost::shared_ptr<Interpolant2d> kInterp,
        double xcen, double ycen, bool cenIsSet, const GSParamsPtr& gsparams) :
    ...,
    _xcentroid(xcen), _ycentroid(ycen), _cenIsSet(cenIsSet)
{
    ...
    
    Nk = data.getYMax()-data.getYMin()+1)
    _ktab = boost::shared_ptr<KTable>(new KTable(Nk, _dk));
    std::complex<double>* kptr = _ktab.getArray();
    const double* ptr = data.getData();
    for(int i=Nk*Nk; i>0; --i, ptr+=2)
        *kptr++ = std::complex<double>(*ptr, *ptr+1);
}

ConstImageView<double> SBInterpolatedKImage::SBInterpolatedKImageImpl::getKData() const
{
    int Nk = _ktab->getN();
    data = reinterpret_cast<const double*>(_ktab->getArray())
    return ConstImageView<double>(data, boost::shared_ptr<double>(),
                                  2*N, Bounds<int>(0,2*N-1,0,N-1));
}
```
I didn't try this out, so there could be bugs in the above, but this should be close.

